w:r.w:t: LO1: Student will be able to identify key considerations for site selection when setting up a MIG
LO2: Student will be able to list the equipment handling practices necessary when preparing a MIG
PA1: Proactivity in researching proper setup methods and precautions
PA2: Attention to detail in following setup procedures and ensuring safety measures are in place

Discussion: Ask the students about their experiences with setting up equipment and any issues they encountered related to site selection or equipment handling. Encourage them to share their insights on how these issues could have been prevented or remedied.
Video: Show a short video (3-4 minutes) demonstrating the proper site selection and equipment handling practices for setting up a MIG. Pause periodically to ask students comprehension questions.

Lecture: Provide a detailed explanation of the key considerations for site selection when setting up a MIG. Discuss factors such as cleanliness, ventilation, proximity to heat sources, and susceptibility to electrical storms. Use diagrams or visuals to illustrate these concepts. Additionally, explain mechanical loading, circuit overloading, and reliable earthing in detail.

Group Work: Divide the class into groups and provide them with a scenario-based exercise to apply the learned concepts of site selection. Each group should identify potential challenges, suggest appropriate solutions, and explain their rationale. Encourage peer review and feedback within the groups.

Role-play: Assign roles to students for a simulated MIG set-up scenario. Each student should be responsible for different tasks related to site selection, equipment handling, and electrical precautions. Observe the students' actions and provide constructive feedback on their performance, emphasizing proper safety measures and attention to detail.

Quiz: Administer a short quiz (10 questions) with multiple-choice options on the key concepts of site selection and equipment handling practices. Provide immediate feedback to the students based on their answers, highlighting common mistakes and reinforcing correct responses.

Reflective Journal: Assign a reflective writing task for the students to complete individually. The students should write about their learning experience in this lesson, focusing on what they learned about site selection and equipment handling practices, how these concepts apply to real-life situations, and any challenges they faced during the role-play exercise. Encourage them to think critically and provide specific examples.

Peer Review: Allow students to exchange their reflective journals with a partner and provide feedback on the content. The students should identify strong points, areas of improvement, and ask questions for clarification. This will help reinforce learning and encourage students to think from multiple perspectives.

Application: Provide the students with a worksheet containing different scenarios related to setting up MIGs in various environments (offices, schools, computer rooms). For each scenario, the students should identify potential risks and hazards, list the required site selection considerations and equipment handling practices, and justify their choices. Encourage students to use their learning from the lesson and apply it to real-life situations.

Take-Home Task: Assign a take-home task for the students. They should research and prepare a brief presentation (5-7 minutes) on a specific aspect of setting up MIGs that they found particularly interesting or challenging during the lesson. This will encourage them to continue their learning outside the classroom and apply it in practical situations.
